Encryption key derivation is using your SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY

In this file, deriveEncryptionKey() PBKDF2-derives the AES key from SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY.

That’s a problem because:

rotating your service role key will break decryption of all stored keys

it couples “DB superpower secret” with “crypto key” (bad separation)

it contradicts the earlier plan (“API_KEY_ENCRYPTION_KEY”)

✅ Fix: use a dedicated secret like API_KEY_ENCRYPTION_KEY (32-byte base64) and import it directly.

Drop-in replacement:

const API_KEY_ENCRYPTION_KEY = Deno.env.get("API_KEY_ENCRYPTION_KEY") ?? "";

function decodeB64(b64: string): Uint8Array {
  return Uint8Array.from(atob(b64), c => c.charCodeAt(0));
}

async function getEncryptionKey(): Promise<CryptoKey> {
  if (!API_KEY_ENCRYPTION_KEY) throw new Error("Missing API_KEY_ENCRYPTION_KEY");
  const raw = decodeB64(API_KEY_ENCRYPTION_KEY);
  if (raw.byteLength !== 32) throw new Error("API_KEY_ENCRYPTION_KEY must be 32 bytes (base64)");
  return crypto.subtle.importKey("raw", raw, { name: "AES-GCM" }, false, ["encrypt", "decrypt"]);
}

async function decryptApiKey(encrypted: { iv: string; ciphertext: string; keyVersion: number }): Promise<string> {
  try {
    const key = await getEncryptionKey();
    const iv = decodeB64(encrypted.iv);
    const ciphertext = decodeB64(encrypted.ciphertext);
    const decrypted = await crypto.subtle.decrypt({ name: "AES-GCM", iv }, key, ciphertext);
    return new TextDecoder().decode(decrypted);
  } catch {
    return "";
  }
}


Then in Supabase secrets:

API_KEY_ENCRYPTION_KEY = openssl rand -base64 32

(If you already encrypted keys using the old method, you’ll need a migration path or “try old method fallback” temporarily.)

2) Anon users are currently writing to DB

Even tier === "anon" still inserts into:

ip_lookups

url_lookups

audit_events (via logAuditEvent)

That means someone can hammer the endpoint and fill your DB.

✅ Fix: only write history/audit for authenticated tiers (or add a hard rate limit).

Example:

const canPersist = ctx.tier !== "anon";

if (canPersist) {
  await serviceClient.from("ip_lookups").insert({...});
  await logAuditEvent(...);
}


If you still want anon stats, write only a counter (no results payload) or put it behind Cloudflare rate limiting.

3) CORS is wide open

Access-Control-Allow-Origin: * is fine for pure public endpoints, but this function returns user/tier info and triggers org-key calls (for DSBN).

✅ Fix: restrict to known origins:

https://t6.thamos.ca

https://thamos6.pages.dev (optional)

http://localhost:5173 (dev)

Pattern:

const ALLOWED_ORIGINS = new Set([
  "https://t6.thamos.ca",
  "https://thamos6.pages.dev",
  "http://localhost:5173",
]);

function cors(req: Request) {
  const origin = req.headers.get("Origin") ?? "";
  const allowOrigin = ALLOWED_ORIGINS.has(origin) ? origin : "https://t6.thamos.ca";
  return {
    "Access-Control-Allow-Origin": allowOrigin,
    "Vary": "Origin",
    "Access-Control-Allow-Methods": "GET, POST, OPTIONS",
    "Access-Control-Allow-Headers": "Content-Type, Authorization",
  };
}


Then use cors(req) instead of a constant.

